public class Q1 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Startup sequence:");
        System.out.println("1. HelloServlet() — constructor (once)");
        System.out.println("2. init(ServletConfig) — once, for resources/config");
        System.out.println();
        System.out.println("Per-request (runs concurrently for 2 requests):");
        System.out.println("3a. service(req1, res1) → doGet(req1, res1)  [Thread-1]");
        System.out.println("3b. service(req2, res2) → doGet(req2, res2)  [Thread-2]");
        System.out.println("    Both threads run on the SAME servlet instance");
        System.out.println();
        System.out.println("Shutdown sequence:");
        System.out.println("4. destroy() — once, cleanup resources");
        System.out.println();
        System.out.println("Why only one constructor?");
        System.out.println("Container uses Singleton pattern for servlets.");
        System.out.println("One instance handles all concurrent requests via thread pool.");
        System.out.println("=> Never store request-specific data in instance fields!");
        System.out.println("=> Use local variables in doGet/doPost — each thread has its own stack.");
    }
}

problems.description:
Demonstrate thread safety issues in servlets and how to fix them.

**UNSAFE — instance field shared by all threads:**
```java
@WebServlet("/counter")
public class UnsafeCounterServlet extends HttpServlet {
    private int count = 0; // SHARED — race condition!
    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest req, HttpServletResponse resp) throws IOException {
        count++; // NOT atomic!
        resp.getWriter().println("Count: " + count);
    }
}
```

**SAFE — use AtomicInteger or synchronization:**
```java
@WebServlet("/counter")
public class SafeCounterServlet extends HttpServlet {
    private final AtomicInteger count = new AtomicInteger(0); // thread-safe
    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest req, HttpServletResponse resp) throws IOException {
        int current = count.incrementAndGet();
        resp.getWriter().println("Count: " + current);
    }
}
```

**Key insight:** Servlet instances are shared across threads. Use `AtomicInteger`/`AtomicReference` for shared counters. Use `ThreadLocal` for per-request state. Never use `synchronized` on servlet methods — blocks all requests.

